#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:5
msgid "NumPy 1.20.0 Release Notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:6
msgid ""
"This NumPy release is the largest so made to date, some 684 PRs contributed "
"by 184 people have been merged. See the list of highlights below for more "
"details. The Python versions supported for this release are 3.7-3.9, support "
"for Python 3.6 has been dropped. Highlights are"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:11
msgid ""
"Annotations for NumPy functions. This work is ongoing and improvements can "
"be expected pending feedback from users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:14
msgid ""
"Wider use of SIMD to increase execution speed of ufuncs. Much work has been "
"done in introducing universal functions that will ease use of modern "
"features across different hardware platforms. This work is ongoing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:18
msgid ""
"Preliminary work in changing the dtype and casting implementations in order "
"to provide an easier path to extending dtypes. This work is ongoing but "
"enough has been done to allow experimentation and feedback."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:22
msgid ""
"Extensive documentation improvements comprising some 185 PR merges. This "
"work is ongoing and part of the larger project to improve NumPy's online "
"presence and usefulness to new users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:26
msgid ""
"Further cleanups related to removing Python 2.7. This improves code "
"readability and removes technical debt."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:29
msgid "Preliminary support for the upcoming Cython 3.0."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:33
msgid "New functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:36
msgid "The random.Generator class has a new ``permuted`` function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:37
msgid ""
"The new function differs from ``shuffle`` and ``permutation`` in that the "
"subarrays indexed by an axis are permuted rather than the axis being treated "
"as a separate 1-D array for every combination of the other indexes. For "
"example, it is now possible to permute the rows or columns of a 2-D array."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:42
msgid "(`gh-15121 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15121>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:45
msgid "``sliding_window_view`` provides a sliding window view for numpy arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:46
msgid ""
"`numpy.lib.stride_tricks.sliding_window_view` constructs views on numpy "
"arrays that offer a sliding or moving window access to the array. This "
"allows for the simple implementation of certain algorithms, such as running "
"means."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:50
msgid "(`gh-17394 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17394>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:53
msgid "`numpy.broadcast_shapes` is a new user-facing function"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:54
msgid ""
"`~numpy.broadcast_shapes` gets the resulting shape from broadcasting the "
"given shape tuples against each other."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:57
msgid ""
">>> np.broadcast_shapes((1, 2), (3, 1))\n"
"(3, 2)\n"
"\n"
">>> np.broadcast_shapes(2, (3, 1))\n"
"(3, 2)\n"
"\n"
">>> np.broadcast_shapes((6, 7), (5, 6, 1), (7,), (5, 1, 7))\n"
"(5, 6, 7)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:68
msgid "(`gh-17535 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17535>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:72
msgid "Deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:75
msgid "Using the aliases of builtin types like ``np.int`` is deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:77
msgid ""
"For a long time, ``np.int`` has been an alias of the builtin ``int``. This "
"is repeatedly a cause of confusion for newcomers, and existed mainly for "
"historic reasons."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:81
msgid ""
"These aliases have been deprecated. The table below shows the full list of "
"deprecated aliases, along with their exact meaning. Replacing uses of items "
"in the first column with the contents of the second column will work "
"identically and silence the deprecation warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:86
msgid ""
"The third column lists alternative NumPy names which may occasionally be "
"preferential. See also :ref:`basics.types` for additional details."
msgstr ""

