#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:102
msgid ""
"To give a clear guideline for the vast majority of cases, for the types "
"``bool``, ``object``, ``str`` (and ``unicode``) using the plain version is "
"shorter and clear, and generally a good replacement. For ``float`` and "
"``complex`` you can use ``float64`` and ``complex128`` if you wish to be "
"more explicit about the precision."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:108
msgid ""
"For ``np.int`` a direct replacement with ``np.int_`` or ``int`` is also good "
"and will not change behavior, but the precision will continue to depend on "
"the computer and operating system. If you want to be more explicit and "
"review the current use, you have the following alternatives:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:114
msgid ""
"``np.int64`` or ``np.int32`` to specify the precision exactly. This ensures "
"that results cannot depend on the computer or operating system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:116
msgid ""
"``np.int_`` or ``int`` (the default), but be aware that it depends on the "
"computer and operating system."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:118
msgid "The C types: ``np.cint`` (int), ``np.int_`` (long), ``np.longlong``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:119
msgid ""
"``np.intp`` which is 32bit on 32bit machines 64bit on 64bit machines. This "
"can be the best type to use for indexing."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:122
msgid ""
"When used with ``np.dtype(...)`` or ``dtype=...`` changing it to the NumPy "
"name as mentioned above will have no effect on the output. If used as a "
"scalar with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:126
msgid "np.float(123)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:128
msgid ""
"changing it can subtly change the result.  In this case, the Python version "
"``float(123)`` or ``int(12.)`` is normally preferable, although the NumPy "
"version may be useful for consistency with NumPy arrays (for example, NumPy "
"behaves differently for things like division by zero)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:133
msgid "(`gh-14882 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/14882>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:136
msgid ""
"Passing ``shape=None`` to functions with a non-optional shape argument is "
"deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:137
msgid ""
"Previously, this was an alias for passing ``shape=()``. This deprecation is "
"emitted by `PyArray_IntpConverter` in the C API. If your API is intended to "
"support passing ``None``, then you should check for ``None`` prior to "
"invoking the converter, so as to be able to distinguish ``None`` and ``()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:143
msgid "(`gh-15886 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15886>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:146
msgid "Indexing errors will be reported even when index result is empty"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:147
msgid ""
"In the future, NumPy will raise an IndexError when an integer array index "
"contains out of bound values even if a non-indexed dimension is of length 0. "
"This will now emit a DeprecationWarning. This can happen when the array is "
"previously empty, or an empty slice is involved::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:153
msgid ""
"arr1 = np.zeros((5, 0))\n"
"arr1[[20]]\n"
"arr2 = np.zeros((5, 5))\n"
"arr2[[20], :0]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:158
msgid ""
"Previously the non-empty index ``[20]`` was not checked for correctness. It "
"will now be checked causing a deprecation warning which will be turned into "
"an error. This also applies to assignments."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:162
msgid "(`gh-15900 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15900>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:165
msgid "Inexact matches for ``mode`` and ``searchside`` are deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:166
msgid ""
"Inexact and case insensitive matches for ``mode`` and ``searchside`` were "
"valid inputs earlier and will give a DeprecationWarning now.  For example, "
"below are some example usages which are now deprecated and will give a "
"DeprecationWarning::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:171
msgid ""
"import numpy as np\n"
"arr = np.array([[3, 6, 6], [4, 5, 1]])\n"
"# mode: inexact match\n"
"np.ravel_multi_index(arr, (7, 6), mode=\"clap\")  # should be \"clip\"\n"
"# searchside: inexact match\n"
"np.searchsorted(arr[0], 4, side='random')  # should be \"right\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:178
msgid "(`gh-16056 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16056>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:181
msgid "Deprecation of `numpy.dual`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:182
msgid ""
"The module `numpy.dual` is deprecated.  Instead of importing functions from "
"`numpy.dual`, the functions should be imported directly from NumPy or SciPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:186
msgid "(`gh-16156 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16156>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:189
msgid "``outer`` and ``ufunc.outer`` deprecated for matrix"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:190
msgid ""
"``np.matrix`` use with `~numpy.outer` or generic ufunc outer calls such as "
"``numpy.add.outer``. Previously, matrix was converted to an array here. This "
"will not be done in the future requiring a manual conversion to arrays."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:195
msgid "(`gh-16232 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16232>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:198
msgid "Further Numeric Style types Deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:200
msgid ""
"The remaining numeric-style type codes ``Bytes0``, ``Str0``, ``Uint32``, "
"``Uint64``, and ``Datetime64`` have been deprecated.  The lower-case "
"variants should be used instead.  For bytes and string ``\"S\"`` and "
"``\"U\"`` are further alternatives."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:206 ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:299
#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:451
msgid "(`gh-16554 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16554>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:209
msgid "The ``ndincr`` method of ``ndindex`` is deprecated"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:210
msgid ""
"The documentation has warned against using this function since NumPy 1.8. "
"Use ``next(it)`` instead of ``it.ndincr()``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:213
msgid "(`gh-17233 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17233>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:216
msgid "ArrayLike objects which do not define ``__len__`` and ``__getitem__``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:217
msgid ""
"Objects which define one of the protocols ``__array__``, "
"``__array_interface__``, or ``__array_struct__`` but are not sequences "
"(usually defined by having a ``__len__`` and ``__getitem__``) will behave "
"differently during array-coercion in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:222
msgid ""
"When nested inside sequences, such as ``np.array([array_like])``, these were "
"handled as a single Python object rather than an array. In the future they "
"will behave identically to::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:226
msgid "np.array([np.array(array_like)])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:228
msgid ""
"This change should only have an effect if ``np.array(array_like)`` is not 0-"
"D. The solution to this warning may depend on the object:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:231
msgid ""
"Some array-likes may expect the new behaviour, and users can ignore the "
"warning.  The object can choose to expose the sequence protocol to opt-in to "
"the new behaviour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:234
msgid ""
"For example, ``shapely`` will allow conversion to an array-like using ``line."
"coords`` rather than ``np.asarray(line)``. Users may work around the "
"warning, or use the new convention when it becomes available."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:238
msgid ""
"Unfortunately, using the new behaviour can only be achieved by calling ``np."
"array(array_like)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:241
msgid ""
"If you wish to ensure that the old behaviour remains unchanged, please "
"create an object array and then fill it explicitly, for example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:244
msgid ""
"arr = np.empty(3, dtype=object)\n"
"arr[:] = [array_like1, array_like2, array_like3]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:247
msgid ""
"This will ensure NumPy knows to not enter the array-like and use it as a "
"object instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:250
msgid "(`gh-17973 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17973>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:254
msgid "Future Changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:257
msgid "Arrays cannot be using subarray dtypes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:258
msgid ""
"Array creation and casting using ``np.array(arr, dtype)`` and ``arr."
"astype(dtype)`` will use different logic when ``dtype`` is a subarray dtype "
"such as ``np.dtype(\"(2)i,\")``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:262
msgid "For such a ``dtype`` the following behaviour is true::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:264
msgid ""
"res = np.array(arr, dtype)\n"
"\n"
"res.dtype is not dtype\n"
"res.dtype is dtype.base\n"
"res.shape == arr.shape + dtype.shape"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:270
msgid "But ``res`` is filled using the logic::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:272
msgid ""
"res = np.empty(arr.shape + dtype.shape, dtype=dtype.base)\n"
"res[...] = arr"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:275
msgid ""
"which uses incorrect broadcasting (and often leads to an error). In the "
"future, this will instead cast each element individually, leading to the "
"same result as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:279
msgid "res = np.array(arr, dtype=np.dtype([\"f\", dtype]))[\"f\"]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:281
msgid "Which can normally be used to opt-in to the new behaviour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:283
msgid ""
"This change does not affect ``np.array(list, dtype=\"(2)i,\")`` unless the "
"``list`` itself includes at least one array.  In particular, the behaviour "
"is unchanged for a list of tuples."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:287
msgid "(`gh-17596 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17596>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:291
msgid "Expired deprecations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:293
msgid ""
"The deprecation of numeric style type-codes ``np.dtype(\"Complex64\")`` "
"(with upper case spelling), is expired.  ``\"Complex64\"`` corresponded to "
"``\"complex128\"`` and ``\"Complex32\"`` corresponded to ``\"complex64\"``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:296
msgid ""
"The deprecation of ``np.sctypeNA`` and ``np.typeNA`` is expired. Both have "
"been removed from the public API. Use ``np.typeDict`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:301
msgid ""
"The 14-year deprecation of ``np.ctypeslib.ctypes_load_library`` is expired. "
"Use :func:`~numpy.ctypeslib.load_library` instead, which is identical."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:304
msgid "(`gh-17116 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17116>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:307
msgid "Financial functions removed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:308
msgid ""
"In accordance with NEP 32, the financial functions are removed from NumPy "
"1.20. The functions that have been removed are ``fv``, ``ipmt``, ``irr``, "
"``mirr``, ``nper``, ``npv``, ``pmt``, ``ppmt``, ``pv``, and ``rate``.  These "
"functions are available in the `numpy_financial <https://pypi.org/project/"
"numpy-financial>`_ library."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:315
msgid "(`gh-17067 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17067>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:319
msgid "Compatibility notes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:322
msgid "``isinstance(dtype, np.dtype)`` and not ``type(dtype) is not np.dtype``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:323
msgid ""
"NumPy dtypes are not direct instances of ``np.dtype`` anymore.  Code that "
"may have used ``type(dtype) is np.dtype`` will always return ``False`` and "
"must be updated to use the correct version ``isinstance(dtype, np.dtype)``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:327
msgid ""
"This change also affects the C-side macro ``PyArray_DescrCheck`` if compiled "
"against a NumPy older than 1.16.6. If code uses this macro and wishes to "
"compile against an older version of NumPy, it must replace the macro (see "
"also `C API changes`_ section)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:334
msgid "Same kind casting in concatenate with ``axis=None``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:335
msgid ""
"When `~numpy.concatenate` is called with ``axis=None``, the flattened arrays "
"were cast with ``unsafe``. Any other axis choice uses \"same kind\". That "
"different default has been deprecated and \"same kind\" casting will be used "
"instead. The new ``casting`` keyword argument can be used to retain the old "
"behaviour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:342 ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:816
msgid "(`gh-16134 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16134>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:345
msgid "NumPy Scalars are cast when assigned to arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:347
msgid ""
"When creating or assigning to arrays, in all relevant cases NumPy scalars "
"will now be cast identically to NumPy arrays.  In particular this changes "
"the behaviour in some cases which previously raised an error::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:352
msgid "np.array([np.float64(np.nan)], dtype=np.int64)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:354
msgid ""
"will succeed and return an undefined result (usually the smallest possible "
"integer).  This also affects assignments::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:357
msgid "arr[0] = np.float64(np.nan)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:359
msgid "At this time, NumPy retains the behaviour for::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:361
msgid "np.array(np.float64(np.nan), dtype=np.int64)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:363
msgid "The above changes do not affect Python scalars::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:365
msgid "np.array([float(\"NaN\")], dtype=np.int64)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:367
msgid ""
"remains unaffected (``np.nan`` is a Python ``float``, not a NumPy one). "
"Unlike signed integers, unsigned integers do not retain this special case, "
"since they always behaved more like casting. The following code stops "
"raising an error::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:372
msgid "np.array([np.float64(np.nan)], dtype=np.uint64)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:374
msgid ""
"To avoid backward compatibility issues, at this time assignment from "
"``datetime64`` scalar to strings of too short length remains supported. This "
"means that ``np.asarray(np.datetime64(\"2020-10-10\"), dtype=\"S5\")`` "
"succeeds now, when it failed before.  In the long term this may be "
"deprecated or the unsafe cast may be allowed generally to make assignment of "
"arrays and scalars behave consistently."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:383
msgid "Array coercion changes when Strings and other types are mixed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:385
msgid "When strings and other types are mixed, such as::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:387
msgid "np.array([\"string\", np.float64(3.)], dtype=\"S\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:389
msgid ""
"The results will change, which may lead to string dtypes with longer strings "
"in some cases.  In particularly, if ``dtype=\"S\"`` is not provided any "
"numerical value will lead to a string results long enough to hold all "
"possible numerical values. (e.g. \"S32\" for floats).  Note that you should "
"always provide ``dtype=\"S\"`` when converting non-strings to strings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:395
msgid ""
"If ``dtype=\"S\"`` is provided the results will be largely identical to "
"before, but NumPy scalars (not a Python float like ``1.0``), will still "
"enforce a uniform string length::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:399
msgid ""
"np.array([np.float64(3.)], dtype=\"S\")  # gives \"S32\"\n"
"np.array([3.0], dtype=\"S\")  # gives \"S3\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:402
msgid "Previously the first version gave the same result as the second."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:406
msgid "Array coercion restructure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:408
msgid ""
"Array coercion has been restructured.  In general, this should not affect "
"users.  In extremely rare corner cases where array-likes are nested::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:411
msgid "np.array([array_like1])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:413
msgid "Things will now be more consistent with::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:415
msgid "np.array([np.array(array_like1)])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:417
msgid ""
"This can subtly change output for some badly defined array-likes. One "
"example for this are array-like objects which are not also sequences of "
"matching shape. In NumPy 1.20, a warning will be given when an array-like is "
"not also a sequence (but behaviour remains identical, see deprecations). If "
"an array like is also a sequence (defines ``__getitem__`` and ``__len__``) "
"NumPy will now only use the result given by ``__array__``, "
"``__array_interface__``, or ``__array_struct__``. This will result in "
"differences when the (nested) sequence describes a different shape."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:427
msgid "(`gh-16200 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16200>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:430
msgid ""
"Writing to the result of `numpy.broadcast_arrays` will export readonly "
"buffers"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:432
msgid ""
"In NumPy 1.17 `numpy.broadcast_arrays` started warning when the resulting "
"array was written to. This warning was skipped when the array was used "
"through the buffer interface (e.g. ``memoryview(arr)``). The same thing will "
"now occur for the two protocols ``__array_interface__``, and "
"``__array_struct__`` returning read-only buffers instead of giving a warning."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:438
msgid "(`gh-16350 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16350>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:441
msgid "Numeric-style type names have been removed from type dictionaries"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:443
msgid ""
"To stay in sync with the deprecation for ``np.dtype(\"Complex64\")`` and "
"other numeric-style (capital case) types.  These were removed from ``np."
"sctypeDict`` and ``np.typeDict``.  You should use the lower case versions "
"instead.  Note that ``\"Complex64\"`` corresponds to ``\"complex128\"`` and "
"``\"Complex32\"`` corresponds to ``\"complex64\"``.  The numpy style (new) "
"versions, denote the full size and not the size of the real/imaginary part."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:454
msgid ""
"The ``operator.concat`` function now raises TypeError for array arguments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:455
msgid ""
"The previous behavior was to fall back to addition and add the two arrays, "
"which was thought to be unexpected behavior for a concatenation function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:458
msgid "(`gh-16570 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16570>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:461
msgid "``nickname`` attribute removed from ABCPolyBase"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:463
msgid ""
"An abstract property ``nickname`` has been removed from  ``ABCPolyBase`` as "
"it was no longer used in the derived convenience classes. This may affect "
"users who have derived classes from ``ABCPolyBase`` and overridden the "
"methods for representation and display, e.g. ``__str__``, ``__repr__``, "
"``_repr_latex``, etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:469
msgid "(`gh-16589 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16589>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:472
msgid ""
"``float->timedelta`` and ``uint64->timedelta`` promotion will raise a "
"TypeError"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:473
msgid ""
"Float and timedelta promotion consistently raises a TypeError. ``np."
"promote_types(\"float32\", \"m8\")`` aligns with ``np.promote_types(\"m8\", "
"\"float32\")`` now and both raise a TypeError. Previously, ``np."
"promote_types(\"float32\", \"m8\")`` returned ``\"m8\"`` which was "
"considered a bug."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:479
msgid ""
"Uint64 and timedelta promotion consistently raises a TypeError. ``np."
"promote_types(\"uint64\", \"m8\")`` aligns with ``np.promote_types(\"m8\", "
"\"uint64\")`` now and both raise a TypeError. Previously, ``np."
"promote_types(\"uint64\", \"m8\")`` returned ``\"m8\"`` which was considered "
"a bug."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:485
msgid "(`gh-16592 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16592>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:488
msgid "``numpy.genfromtxt`` now correctly unpacks structured arrays"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:489
msgid ""
"Previously, `numpy.genfromtxt` failed to unpack if it was called with "
"``unpack=True`` and a structured datatype was passed to the ``dtype`` "
"argument (or ``dtype=None`` was passed and a structured datatype was "
"inferred). For example::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:494
msgid ""
">>> data = StringIO(\"21 58.0\\n35 72.0\")\n"
">>> np.genfromtxt(data, dtype=None, unpack=True)\n"
"array([(21, 58.), (35, 72.)], dtype=[('f0', '<i8'), ('f1', '<f8')])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:498
msgid ""
"Structured arrays will now correctly unpack into a list of arrays, one for "
"each column::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:501
msgid ""
">>> np.genfromtxt(data, dtype=None, unpack=True)\n"
"[array([21, 35]), array([58., 72.])]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:504
msgid "(`gh-16650 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16650>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:507
msgid ""
"``mgrid``, ``r_``, etc. consistently return correct outputs for non-default "
"precision input"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:508
msgid ""
"Previously, ``np.mgrid[np.float32(0.1):np.float32(0.35):np.float32(0.1),]`` "
"and ``np.r_[0:10:np.complex64(3j)]`` failed to return meaningful output. "
"This bug potentially affects `~numpy.mgrid`, `~numpy.ogrid`, `~numpy.r_`, "
"and `~numpy.c_` when an input with dtype other than the default ``float64`` "
"and ``complex128`` and equivalent Python types were used. The methods have "
"been fixed to handle varying precision correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:515
msgid "(`gh-16815 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16815>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:518
msgid ""
"Boolean array indices with mismatching shapes now properly give "
"``IndexError``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:520
msgid ""
"Previously, if a boolean array index matched the size of the indexed array "
"but not the shape, it was incorrectly allowed in some cases. In other cases, "
"it gave an error, but the error was incorrectly a ``ValueError`` with a "
"message about broadcasting instead of the correct ``IndexError``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:525
msgid ""
"For example, the following used to incorrectly give ``ValueError: operands "
"could not be broadcast together with shapes (2,2) (1,4)``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:528
msgid "np.empty((2, 2))[np.array([[True, False, False, False]])]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:532
msgid ""
"And the following used to incorrectly return ``array([], dtype=float64)``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:534
msgid "np.empty((2, 2))[np.array([[False, False, False, False]])]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:538
msgid ""
"Both now correctly give ``IndexError: boolean index did not match indexed "
"array along dimension 0; dimension is 2 but corresponding boolean dimension "
"is 1``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:542
msgid "(`gh-17010 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17010>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:545
msgid "Casting errors interrupt Iteration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:546
msgid ""
"When iterating while casting values, an error may stop the iteration earlier "
"than before. In any case, a failed casting operation always returned "
"undefined, partial results. Those may now be even more undefined and "
"partial. For users of the ``NpyIter`` C-API such cast errors will now cause "
"the `iternext()` function to return 0 and thus abort iteration. Currently, "
"there is no API to detect such an error directly. It is necessary to check "
"``PyErr_Occurred()``, which may be problematic in combination with "
"``NpyIter_Reset``. These issues always existed, but new API could be added "
"if required by users."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:559
msgid "(`gh-17029 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17029>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:562
msgid "f2py generated code may return unicode instead of byte strings"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:563
msgid ""
"Some byte strings previously returned by f2py generated code may now be "
"unicode strings. This results from the ongoing Python2 -> Python3 cleanup."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:566
msgid "(`gh-17068 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17068>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:569
msgid ""
"The first element of the ``__array_interface__[\"data\"]`` tuple  must be an "
"integer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:570
msgid ""
"This has been the documented interface for many years, but there was still "
"code that would accept a byte string representation of the pointer address. "
"That code has been removed, passing the address as a byte string will now "
"raise an error."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:575
msgid "(`gh-17241 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17241>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:578
msgid "poly1d respects the dtype of all-zero argument"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:579
msgid ""
"Previously, constructing an instance of ``poly1d`` with all-zero "
"coefficients would cast the coefficients to ``np.float64``. This affected "
"the output dtype of methods which construct ``poly1d`` instances internally, "
"such as ``np.polymul``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:584
msgid "(`gh-17577 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17577>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:587
msgid "The numpy.i file for swig is Python 3 only."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:588
msgid ""
"Uses of Python 2.7 C-API functions have been updated to Python 3 only. Users "
"who need the old version should take it from an older version of NumPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:591
msgid "(`gh-17580 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17580>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:594
msgid "Void dtype discovery in ``np.array``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:595
msgid ""
"In calls using ``np.array(..., dtype=\"V\")``, ``arr.astype(\"V\")``, and "
"similar a TypeError will now be correctly raised unless all elements have "
"the identical void length. An example for this is::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:599
msgid "np.array([b\"1\", b\"12\"], dtype=\"V\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:601
msgid ""
"Which previously returned an array with dtype ``\"V2\"`` which cannot "
"represent ``b\"1\"`` faithfully."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:604
msgid "(`gh-17706 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17706>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:608
msgid "C API changes"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:611
msgid "The ``PyArray_DescrCheck`` macro is modified"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:612
msgid ""
"The ``PyArray_DescrCheck`` macro has been updated since NumPy 1.16.6 to be::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:614
msgid ""
"#define PyArray_DescrCheck(op) PyObject_TypeCheck(op, &PyArrayDescr_Type)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:616
msgid ""
"Starting with NumPy 1.20 code that is compiled against an earlier version "
"will be API incompatible with NumPy 1.20. The fix is to either compile "
"against 1.16.6 (if the NumPy 1.16 release is the oldest release you wish to "
"support), or manually inline the macro by replacing it with the new "
"definition::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:622
msgid "PyObject_TypeCheck(op, &PyArrayDescr_Type)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:624
msgid "which is compatible with all NumPy versions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:628
msgid "Size of ``np.ndarray`` and ``np.void_`` changed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:629
msgid ""
"The size of the ``PyArrayObject`` and ``PyVoidScalarObject`` structures have "
"changed.  The following header definition has been removed::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:633
msgid "#define NPY_SIZEOF_PYARRAYOBJECT (sizeof(PyArrayObject_fields))"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:635
msgid ""
"since the size must not be considered a compile time constant: it will "
"change for different runtime versions of NumPy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:638
msgid ""
"The most likely relevant use are potential subclasses written in C which "
"will have to be recompiled and should be updated.  Please see the "
"documentation for :c:type:`PyArrayObject` for more details and contact the "
"NumPy developers if you are affected by this change."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:643
msgid ""
"NumPy will attempt to give a graceful error but a program expecting a fixed "
"structure size may have undefined behaviour and likely crash."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:646
msgid "(`gh-16938 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16938>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:650
msgid "New Features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:653
msgid ""
"``where`` keyword argument for ``numpy.all`` and ``numpy.any`` functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:654
msgid ""
"The keyword argument ``where`` is added and allows to only consider "
"specified elements or subaxes from an array in the Boolean evaluation of "
"``all`` and ``any``. This new keyword is available to the functions ``all`` "
"and ``any`` both via ``numpy`` directly or in the methods of ``numpy."
"ndarray``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:659 ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:672
msgid ""
"Any broadcastable Boolean array or a scalar can be set as ``where``. It "
"defaults to ``True`` to evaluate the functions for all elements in an array "
"if ``where`` is not set by the user. Examples are given in the documentation "
"of the functions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:666
msgid ""
"``where`` keyword argument for ``numpy`` functions ``mean``, ``std``, ``var``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:667
msgid ""
"The keyword argument ``where`` is added and allows to limit the scope in the "
"calculation of ``mean``, ``std`` and ``var`` to only a subset of elements. "
"It is available both via ``numpy`` directly or in the methods of ``numpy."
"ndarray``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:677
msgid "(`gh-15852 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15852>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:680
msgid ""
"``norm=backward``, ``forward`` keyword options for ``numpy.fft`` functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:681
msgid ""
"The keyword argument option ``norm=backward`` is added as an alias for "
"``None`` and acts as the default option; using it has the direct transforms "
"unscaled and the inverse transforms scaled by ``1/n``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:685
msgid ""
"Using the new keyword argument option ``norm=forward`` has the direct "
"transforms scaled by ``1/n`` and the inverse transforms unscaled (i.e. "
"exactly opposite to the default option ``norm=backward``)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:689
msgid "(`gh-16476 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16476>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:692
msgid "NumPy is now typed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:693
msgid ""
"Type annotations have been added for large parts of NumPy. There is also a "
"new `numpy.typing` module that contains useful types for end-users. The "
"currently available types are"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:697
msgid "``ArrayLike``: for objects that can be coerced to an array"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:698
msgid "``DtypeLike``: for objects that can be coerced to a dtype"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:700
msgid "(`gh-16515 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16515>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:703
msgid "``numpy.typing`` is accessible at runtime"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:704
msgid ""
"The types in ``numpy.typing`` can now be imported at runtime. Code like the "
"following will now work:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:707
msgid ""
"from numpy.typing import ArrayLike\n"
"x: ArrayLike = [1, 2, 3, 4]"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:712
msgid "(`gh-16558 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16558>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:715
msgid "New ``__f2py_numpy_version__`` attribute for f2py generated modules."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:716
msgid ""
"Because f2py is released together with NumPy, ``__f2py_numpy_version__`` "
"provides a way to track the version f2py used to generate the module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:719
msgid "(`gh-16594 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/16594>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:722
msgid "``mypy`` tests can be run via runtests.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:723
msgid "Currently running mypy with the NumPy stubs configured requires either:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:726
msgid "Installing NumPy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:727
msgid "Adding the source directory to MYPYPATH and linking to the ``mypy.ini``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:729
msgid ""
"Both options are somewhat inconvenient, so add a ``--mypy`` option to "
"runtests that handles setting things up for you. This will also be useful in "
"the future for any typing codegen since it will ensure the project is built "
"before type checking."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:734
msgid "(`gh-17123 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17123>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:737
msgid "Negation of user defined BLAS/LAPACK detection order"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:738
msgid ""
"`~numpy.distutils` allows negation of libraries when determining BLAS/LAPACK "
"libraries. This may be used to remove an item from the library resolution "
"phase, i.e. to disallow NetLIB libraries one could do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:743
msgid "NPY_BLAS_ORDER='^blas' NPY_LAPACK_ORDER='^lapack' python setup.py build"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:747
msgid "That will use any of the accelerated libraries instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:749
msgid "(`gh-17219 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17219>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:752
msgid "Allow passing optimizations arguments to asv build"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:753
msgid ""
"It is now possible to pass  ``-j``, ``--cpu-baseline``, ``--cpu-dispatch`` "
"and ``--disable-optimization`` flags to ASV build when the ``--bench-"
"compare`` argument is used."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:757
msgid "(`gh-17284 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17284>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:760
msgid "The NVIDIA HPC SDK nvfortran compiler is now supported"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:761
msgid ""
"Support for the nvfortran compiler, a version of pgfortran, has been added."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:763
msgid "(`gh-17344 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17344>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:766
msgid "``dtype`` option for ``cov`` and ``corrcoef``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:767
msgid ""
"The ``dtype`` option is now available for `numpy.cov` and `numpy.corrcoef`. "
"It specifies which data-type the returned result should have. By default the "
"functions still return a `numpy.float64` result."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:771
msgid "(`gh-17456 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/17456>`__)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:775
msgid "Improvements"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:778
msgid "Improved string representation for polynomials (``__str__``)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:780
msgid ""
"The string representation (``__str__``) of all six polynomial types in "
"`numpy.polynomial` has been updated to give the polynomial as a mathematical "
"expression instead of an array of coefficients. Two package-wide formats for "
"the polynomial expressions are available - one using Unicode characters for "
"superscripts and subscripts, and another using only ASCII characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../release/1.20.0-notes.rst:786
msgid "(`gh-15666 <https://github.com/numpy/numpy/pull/15666>`__)"
msgstr ""

